/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

I don't know if fear responses really line up with personality at all but mine kind of did so I thought this would be a good question potentially

ISFJ
I usually freeze or become very quiet both when I'm alerted to a possible threat and when I am aware that there is one, though I also inch toward "fight". I don't like having my back toward people or things that make me feel unsafe even to run away, so I don't run even though I'm a bit of a coward. Part of it also probably due to paralysis caused by indecision.
In some cases I very much have what feels like a primal urge to sucker punch a person because of how anxious and unsafe they are making me feel, but that's frowned upon unfortunately.

Trying to accept that I am different from others but that I still have some worth. It's harder some days than others. I find it hard to relate to others and yet I am most inspired by others. >What prophantasia would be like in this context? And (slightly unrelated, but since I've brought up prophantasia...) how would hallucinations differ from prophantasic constructions based on invasive thoughts?
I believe that would still be simple imagination, since those images would be recognized as voluntary mental constructons. The FEP pertains to how biological (re)action takes place. With motion, for example, it isn't just that you decide to move, but that your brain "predicts" that you are in a different position, then forces your body to minimize errors in the prediction. (I'm not a neuroscientist, but I think research has been showing something like this is what happens)
>Well, yeah, with brain just filling the gaps of "blanks" in data flow to complement eyesight perception for where it's lacking
It's partially that, but this goes quite a bit further. Your brain isn't just filling in the gaps of perception, it supplies the whole blueprint and base structure. When something like a psychoactive drug disrupts this structure, the same object can now be seen as something else completely, even when the sensory faculties themselves are relatively untouched.
>"FEP is beneficial when it's correct" and "FEP is beneficial when it's wrong" sounds a bit sloppy
My understanding is that there isn't really a way to "violate" it, it's simply how things work. Friston had the idea when as a boy he was watching woodlice scurrying around and realized there was no "purpose" to their actions; they simply moved faster in the sun and slower in the shade.

>2. In this context, what's exactly to make of decisions of will that go against the optimization inclinations of Free Energy Principle?
I think the important point is that principle can't really be violated in "this" world, only through the unstructured innocence of the unconscious, the secret world behind it. The principle necessarily follows from this way of bringing the world under a system of abstract representation (in the same way as something like entropy), but the unconscious knows of no such representations.
>As an example of what I mean for {2}, additionally it can be chosen for one to allow to gaslight oneself with shifts of expectations to move the levers of the material body through the Free Energy Principle, feeding with the types of adjustments deemed necessary.
Yes, it is sort of the underlying principle of cybernetics. With cybernetics you can change your "priors" by altering your environmental feedback loops. Then you have a large degree of control over your reality - if you choose to. But not every cybernetic organism would have a high level of control, since they are also controlled within larger cybernetic ensembles of society. posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>72074325
>Not just mundane, but also over-complicated where it's not necessary
>It's pointed out it's not easily falsifiable in its principles
I think many researchers don't understand it properly, as Friston himself said:
> "the free energy principle is what it is - a principle. Like Hamilton's principle of stationary action, it cannot be falsified. It cannot be disproven. In fact, there's not much you can do with it, unless you ask whether measurable systems conform to the principle."
In other words, like entropy, it isn't really "scientific," but more like a metaphysical principle, and thus a transcendental illusion rather than a ground truth about reality. Hence why I said I don't fully adhere to it - it doesn't give any ultimate truth, but helps understand a certain mode of life and way of representing the world. To the original point, in relation to sensing; yes you sense the world, but is it just "you" that senses, in a merely passive manner? Or is there something else, of very different origins, that inscribes how this process is to take place within you? You also think and feel, but is it truly your thinking and feeling? I don't claim to have answers, but it's fun to look at things differently! I think it's bad for the mind to be trapped.

> Overall, extraverted feeling is concerned with phenomena to be harmonious with its external environment. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jungian_cognitive_functions)

> Extraverted Feeling focuses on shared values, the greater good, and emotional dynamics. Extraverted Feeling types (FJ personalities) tend to believe that individual wants and desires should come second to the overall harmony or well-being of the group at large. (https://www.psychologyjunkie.com/what-is-extraverted-feeling/#h-what-is-extraverted-feeling-fe)

> Extraverted Feeling seeks to judge the value of objects based on objective factors, while completely suppressing the subject. That means assigning value to objects purely based on objective and universal values and sentiments.
> Fe seeks to stay in full alignment and influence of the objective value standards.
> Source: Jung, Psychological Types - Page 595 (https://wiki.personality-database.com/books/mbti-and-cognitive-functions/page/fe-extroverted-feeling)

Any Feeling dom, whether it's Fi or Fe, can be stubborn about their values. The difference here is that Fi seeks internal harmony, while Fe seeks external harmony.

>>72132724
Yes, so, imagination is not in the brain's ledger of expected sensory data, so there is no "surprise" where it does not fit with the senses, and therefore no free energy/uncertainty.

It should be said also that the brain doesn't just make singular predictions about what it sees, but a constant stream of predictions that collide with the inbound flow of sensory data. "That person in the blue uniform is probably a police officer," "If they are, how does that affect the various objects of the scene?" And so on. Abstract knowledge/concepts, then, are also used by your brain to shape how you sense reality.
Interestingly, according to this view, perception and reasoning are both part of the same fundamental process, and rely on the same source (base assumptions, priors, etc.). And, as we talked before, that leads to an important question, namely, where does that source come from? Are they prefabricated in the unconscious (such as with archetypes and Oedipal figures), or implanted and programmed into you from without?

This also goes back to your original point about intuition, and whether it could be considered a kind of sensing, where the brain maybe has to make sense of unconscious data in a similar top-down manner.
I just think that intuition doesn't operate on "priors" in the same way that the other functions do, hence why it risks erupting into schizophrenia. But this also raises the question of whether intuition should even be considered a cognitive function alongside the others at all, rather than something undefinable that operates within the interstices of sanity.

Anyway, sorry for dragging this on, but it's a very complex topic, so thank you for humoring me.

Hello, Anon, need some help? A shoulder to cry on? Sit down and let's have a little chat.

STEP #1, HYGIENE AND HOME:
Brush your teeth twice a day, morning and evening. Scrub'em good with all the movements you can think of, circles, up and down, lateral, front and behind. This will take somewhere around 2 minutes. Floss once a day.
Moisturize your face with a cream after washing your face in the morning.
Depending on how much you sweat shower every or every second day.
Get a haircut every 2 months. If you are balding just cut'em short, anything else looks shit and insecure about it.
If your clothes are ripped, stretched and discolored as shit, get some new ones. Basic, monotone, cheap shirts will do just fine. Again, depending on your sweat wear'em between 1 and 3 days, then change. If you got a pile of dirty rags wash it.

This brings us to your home. Doesn't matter if you live alone or with your parents, clean your dwelling once a week. Empty bottles and packages are to be thrown away immediately, instead of hoarded. It's no work if you do it this way. Used plates, glasses, etc., are to be washed off immediately after use. Again, if you do it like this, it's way less work than cleaning off a whole pile of them.
Changing bed sheets and vacuuming the place once a week.

A healthy mind lives in a clean body, living in a clean place. All that grime on yourself and around you poisons your mind. This regime gets rid of that without too much effort. You will also feel a sense of accomplishment, which boosts you for what comes next, LEAVING THE HOUSE

STEP #2, LEAVE HOUSE:
Go out every day. Do long walks of atleast 2 hours. Explore your city, your surroundings. Go into alleys you never walked before. Whenever you think, oh whats there or I never was there or anything similiat, thats where you go!
Do not ask yourself shit, like "whats the use? Enjoy the moment, do not drown out your surrounsings with your depressive thoughts.

Observe them, what they wear, their hair, makeup, tatoos, whatever and throw them a compliment, ask them where they got it from, what meaning it holds to them. When the convo naturally found its end, say your goodbye and go on your way.

STEP #4, GET A REAL HOBBY:
You should be prepared now, physically and mentally, to go out there and take the risk of trying new stuff, which will include meeting people doing the same stuff, but you are ready for that.
